Svelte and Solid both need an accessor when query inputs are reactive, so the query is rebuilt when inputs change.

```ts
// Svelte
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const sub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  projectId ? app.todos.where({ projectId }) : undefined,
);
```

```ts
// Solid
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: projectId() ? app.todos.where({ projectId: projectId() }) : undefined,
}));
```

Use `db.batch(...)` for two optimistic UI writes that should appear locally together as soon as the batch commits.

Use `db.transaction(...)` for two writes that must stay staged until authority accepts them, then become visible together and be awaited as a unit for global durability.

```ts
const batchResult = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
```

```ts
const txResult = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await txResult.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Use the conventional chunked-file tables exactly as expected by Jazz helpers:

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({
    data: s.bytes(),
  }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Permissions should make `uploads` the access root: allow `uploads` read/insert/update/delete for the owner, allow narrowly scoped direct `files` and `file_parts` inserts because helpers create them before the parent row exists, then inherit file read/delete from `uploads.fileId` and part read/delete from `files.partIds`. Do not grant broad public reads; keep files write-once and store the returned `file.id` on the parent upload row.

Upload with an edge write tier so success means every chunk reached edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });

const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Profile photo",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For download, request the needed read tier and distinguish incomplete local data from a missing file:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  // render/use blob
} catch (err) {
  if (err.name === "IncompleteFileDataError") {
    // local chunks or metadata are incomplete; show retry/loading state
  } else if (err.name === "FileNotFoundError") {
    // file row is not visible or was deleted
  } else {
    throw err;
  }
}
```

Use `loadFileAsStream(...)` instead when sequential consumption is better. `IncompleteFileDataError` covers invalid metadata, missing parts, or part-size mismatch; it is a different product state from file absence.

Delete in dependency order while inherited permissions still exist: load the parent upload first, load its file through the still-valid relationship, delete every part, delete the file row, then delete the upload row.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the parent first, or the inherited delete permission for `files` and `file_parts` can disappear before cleanup finishes.
